    <summary>
      <para>Introduction to Auto-Input Protection (AIP).</para>
    </summary>
    <introduction>
      <para>
        This document provides an overview of AIP.  To get started using AIP right away, see <link xlink:href="733151f0-b1f8-4bb7-907e-907b37da532f" />.
      </para>
    </introduction>
    <section>
      <title>Overview</title>
      <content>
        <autoOutline />
        <para>
          The ClassDefinition example consists of only a single snippet (#1) in
          multiple languages.  Here's how to reference it in a conceptual topic:
        </para>
        <codeReference>ClassDefinition#1</codeReference>
        <para>
          DimVariable is an example that consists of multiple snippets (String and Int32).
          Here's how to reference the String snippet:
        </para>
        <codeReference>DimVariable#String</codeReference>
        <para>
          Here's how to generate a code sample of both DimVariable snippets combined:
        </para>
        <codeReference>DimVariable#String,Int32</codeReference>
        <para>
          Auto-Input Protection (AIP) is an extensible ASP.NET web control that provides CAPTCHA protection for your blogs, forums, wikis and websites, greatly reducing the likelihood of
          unwanted form submission from automated spam and hacks.
        </para>
        <para>
          AIP is an open source project that is available on CodePlex at <externalLink><linkText>http://www.codeplex.com/AIP</linkText><linkUri>http://www.codeplex.com/AIP</linkUri></externalLink> 
					for use under the terms and conditions of the <externalLink><linkText>Microsoft Reciprocal License (Ms-RL)</linkText><linkUri>http://www.codeplex.com/AIP/license</linkUri></externalLink>.  
					The complete source code is <externalLink><linkText>available for download</linkText><linkUri>https://www.codeplex.com/Release/ProjectReleases.aspx</linkUri></externalLink> 
					along with the installer and for <externalLink><linkText>online browsing</linkText><linkUri>http://www.codeplex.com/aip/SourceControl/ListDownloadableCommits.aspx</linkUri></externalLink>.
        </para>
        <para>
          DocProject was built from the ground up by <externalLink><linkText>Dave Sexton</linkText><linkUri>http://davesexton.com/blog</linkUri></externalLink>.  
					The latest release is written in C# 3.0 but the output is built against the Microsoft .NET Framework 2.0 so that it's compatible with both Visual Studio 2005 and 2008, 
        as well as Visual Web Developer 2005 and 2008.
        </para>
      </content>
